---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';

const post = postBySlug('electric-shower-replacement-cumnock')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Plumbing & bathrooms',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'shower replacement Ayrshire', 'Mira shower installation Kilmarnock', 'Triton shower Cumnock', 'electric shower fitters'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: [{ '@type': 'Place', name: 'Cumnock, Scotland' }],
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        Electric showers do not last forever. Most of them give you seven to
        ten years if you are lucky with your water. Here is how we tell —
        in a Cumnock bathroom, with the cover off — whether it is worth
        repairing or time to put a new unit on the wall.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <p>
        Electric shower calls are one of our most common
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/plumbing/`}>plumbing</a> jobs in
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/cumnock/`}>Cumnock</a>, and the rest of
        East Ayrshire is much the same. The water here is mid-hardness,
        which is enough to limescale a heating element to death inside a
        decade, and the post-war housing stock around Netherthird and
        Barshare tends to have showers that were last swapped when the
        bathroom was last refitted — often the late 1990s or early 2000s.
      </p>
      <p>
        If your shower is doing any of the things in the next section, it is
        worth having a proper look at.
      </p>

      <h2>Signs it's time to replace — not just repair</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Temperature fluctuating wildly</strong> while you are
          under it. This is the classic "scalded then freezing" cycle and
          usually means the thermostatic stat or the heating element is on
          its way out. On a unit older than 8 years it is rarely worth the
          part.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Tripping the breaker when you turn it on.</strong> This is
          often a failed heating element going to earth. Dangerous — do not
          keep resetting it. Turn the circuit off at the consumer unit and
          ring us.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Weak flow even with the head descaled.</strong> You clean
          the head, nothing changes. Likely a blocked solenoid, inlet filter
          or internal pressure valve. On a 7+ year unit these parts can be
          scarce — a replacement unit is often the same cost as the repair.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>A burning-plastic smell</strong> when it is running. Stop
          using it, turn it off, ring us. This is a thermal fuse or a
          scorched terminal and it is not a "finish your shower first"
          situation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Visible corrosion or water staining</strong> on the
          casing from the outside. Means the internals are wet. Replace.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>It is 10+ years old and working.</strong> Honestly — we
          would still swap it, because the next failure is usually the one
          that floods a flat below.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Pump vs unit — how to tell</h2>
      <p>
        A common confusion. An <strong>electric shower</strong> heats cold
        water on demand from a single cold-water feed. A <strong>pumped
        shower</strong> (mixer with a pump, or a power shower) mixes hot
        and cold from the house system and a separate pump boosts the
        pressure. They fail for different reasons and cost different
        amounts to fix.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Electric shower faults</strong> are usually heating
          element, solenoid or pressure switch. Problem lives inside the
          wall unit.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pump faults</strong> (on a pumped mixer) are usually the
          pump itself — in the airing cupboard or under the bath. You can
          often hear a pump failing: it rattles, stutters, or stops
          starting when you open the valve. New pump is £180 to £320
          fitted depending on whether the existing pipework suits.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Photo of the unit on WhatsApp and we will tell you which one you
        are dealing with inside five minutes.
      </p>

      <h2>Brands we fit</h2>
      <p>
        We fit the three brands that actually survive Ayrshire water and
        are easy to get parts for:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Mira</strong> — Mira Sport, Mira Advance, Mira Jump. The
          workhorse. Parts are everywhere. Ten-year working life is
          realistic. Most of our Cumnock and Auchinleck customers end up
          back on Mira for a reason.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Triton</strong> — Triton T80, T90sr. Cheaper than Mira
          out the door and perfectly fine for a tenant property or an
          every-so-often en suite. Parts are plentiful.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Bristan</strong> — Bristan Joy, Bristan Glee. We fit
          these when asked — good feel and good finish, though we think
          the service life sits a shade under Mira for the same price.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Unit + fit price bands — all in</h2>
      <p>
        Honest price bands for a <strong>like-for-like</strong> electric
        shower swap in Cumnock and the surrounding KA18 postcode — unit
        supplied and fitted, existing cable and water feed reused, old
        unit removed:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>£180 to £240</strong> — entry-level swap. Triton T80 or
          similar, 8.5 kW. Fits the slot of a dead budget unit. Works, no
          frills.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>£240 to £320</strong> — mid-range. Mira Jump or Triton
          T90sr, 9.5 kW to 10.5 kW. Phased shutdown, better flow, tidier
          handset. This is where we nudge most customers.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>£320 to £420</strong> — premium. Mira Sport Max or Mira
          Advance, 10.8 kW with digital thermostat. Proper ten-year unit.
          Worth it on a forever-home bathroom.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Prices are all-in for the handyman side — unit, handset, hose,
        wall mounts, silicone, and the labour to remove the old one and
        fit the new one. Usually a two-hour visit.
      </p>

      <h2>When an electrician has to be involved</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>We are a handyman business, not a licensed electrical
        contractor.</strong> Swapping a like-for-like electric shower onto
        an existing, correctly-sized, correctly-wired circuit we do
        routinely — it is maintenance, not a new install. But if any of
        the following applies, we bring in a Part-P electrician to handle
        the circuit side, and we will coordinate that visit for you:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          The cable gauge to the existing shower is undersized for the
          new unit (going up from 8.5 kW to 10.8 kW often needs a heavier
          cable — typically 10mm² instead of 6mm²).
        </li>
        <li>
          There is no dedicated circuit — some older Ayrshire houses
          have showers spurred off a ring, which is not compliant.
        </li>
        <li>
          The existing pull-cord isolator is broken or missing.
        </li>
        <li>
          The RCD on the consumer unit does not trip correctly when tested.
        </li>
        <li>
          The circuit has never had an EICR and the house is a rental —
          we recommend one alongside the swap.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        When the electrician is needed we get two trades out on the same
        day wherever possible so your bathroom is not out of use for a
        week. You get one consolidated invoice from us.
      </p>

      <h2>Warranty</h2>
      <p>
        Mira, Triton and Bristan all carry manufacturer warranties of
        between 2 and 5 years on the unit — check the box for yours. We
        warrant the fit for 12 months against leak or failure caused by
        installation. Faults traceable to the manufacturer go back through
        the manufacturer's warranty process; we will help you register it
        and handle the claim if there is ever a problem.
      </p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>
      <h3>How long does a shower swap take?</h3>
      <p>
        Two hours on the van, typically. If the electrician needs to run a
        new cable, add a morning.
      </p>
      <h3>Can you do it same-day if mine has died?</h3>
      <p>
        Often yes — we carry a Mira Jump and a Triton T80 on the van most
        days as stock swap-outs. WhatsApp Aidan a photo of the failed unit
        and the cable in the loft or cupboard and we will give you a
        straight answer.
      </p>
      <h3>Do you fit digital showers or rainheads?</h3>
      <p>
        Mira Advance yes. Full gravity-fed rainhead installs with new
        mixer valves — we quote on request, they are a bigger job.
      </p>
      <h3>Will you take the old unit away?</h3>
      <p>
        Always. All waste from our jobs leaves with us. You pay the price
        on the quote and nothing extra.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />

  <CTABlock
    heading="Shower dead? We'll have it swapped by teatime."
    sub="Photo the unit and the pull-cord cable on WhatsApp. We'll quote you a firm price before we get in the van."
    location="Cumnock"
  />
</BaseLayout>
